  "topic_name": "Pollution and Conservation",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Pollution is the introduction of harmful substances into the environment. Air pollution includes particulate matter, SO2, NOx, CO, causing respiratory problems, acid rain, and global warming. Water pollution sources include industrial waste, sewage, and agricultural runoff, causing eutrophication and health hazards. Soil pollution from pesticides, fertilizers, and waste affects soil fertility. Noise pollution affects hearing and causes stress. The greenhouse effect traps heat, causing global warming. Ozone layer depletion by CFCs allows harmful UV radiation. Conservation includes in-situ (national parks, sanctuaries, biosphere reserves) and ex-situ (zoos, gene banks) methods. Sustainable development meets present needs without compromising future generations. The 3Rs (Reduce, Reuse, Recycle) help minimize waste.",
    "rules": [
      "Air pollution: particulates, SO2, NOx, CO; causes respiratory issues, acid rain",
      "Greenhouse effect: CO2, CH4 trap heat; causes global warming",
      "Ozone depletion: CFCs destroy O3 layer; UV radiation increases",
      "Water pollution: eutrophication from excess nutrients",
      "In-situ conservation: national parks, wildlife sanctuaries, biosphere reserves",
      "Ex-situ conservation: zoos, botanical gardens, gene banks",
      "Sustainable development: development without compromising future needs",
      "3Rs: Reduce, Reuse, Recycle"
    ]
  },
